<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900803-0041</DOCNO><DOCID>900803-0041.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Continental Airlines Holdings Inc.:   First Profit Is Reported   For a Quarter Since 1986</HL><DATE>08/03/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C5</SO><CO>   CTA</CO><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><LP>   Continental Airlines Holdings Inc., Houston, recorded itsfirst profitable quarter since late 1986, but it would haveposted another loss without special gains totaling $123.2million at its Continental unit.   In addition, the parent, which recently changed its namefrom Texas Air Corp., lost control of its Eastern Airlinesunit early in the second quarter and no longer has to reportthat troubled carrier's losses.</LP><TEXT>   For the quarter, Continental Airlines Holdings had netincome of $98.3 million, or $2.21 a share, on revenue of$1.51 billion. In the year-ago quarter, it reported a netloss of $109.3 million, or a loss of $2.88 a share on revenueof $1.4 billion.   The company said it was excluding the results of EasternAirlines from April 19 on, when a bankruptcy judge appointeda trustee to take control of the unit. As a result of anaccounting change, then, the Continental Holdings'second-quarter results include only 18 days of Easternresults, in which the financially ailing carrier had a lossof $12.6 million on revenue of $115.9 million.   For the six months, the parent company reported a net lossof $8.8 million, or 51 cents a share, on revenue of $3.37billion, compared with a net loss of $364.9 million onrevenue of $3.28 billion.</TEXT></DOC>